<br>
Some of the older SCI-FI is still very worth reading. Robert Heinlien has some great books (Moon is a Harsh Mistress, Friday, Stranger in a Strange Land). <br>
<br>
Assimov's Foundation series is insane (Dont bother with the new trilogy that's not by him, it's a shame 3 excellent writes suck so bad in it)<br>
<br>
David Brin is awsome, read Sundiver, the Uplift Series (Startide Rising, Uplift War and uh, I forget). Earth is also an excellent book, although kinda scary.<br>
<br>
Fantasy, well: <br>
Robert Jordan needs to fucking tie up some ends. I havent read the last book yet and the book before that he cleared the taint, so maybe there is some hope. I liked the Fire and Ice series ok, but I really think that the best post LOTR is the Fiest Riftwar Saga. Very well done &quot;Classic&quot; Fantasy. <br>
The Dragonlance series are ok, kinda simple though. <br>
I also like the newish series by Kate Elliot, she was a pretty shitty SciFi writer but does a great job at fantasy, except she underestimates the ability of mideval engineering.<br>
Hmm, Robin Hobb is kind of cool too, and doens't copy from everyone else, but occasionally you want to slap her protagonists.<br>
